#compdef git-proxy
# =============================================================================
# git-proxy — FINOS's "Deploy custom push protections
#          and policies on top of Git" — a Node.js
#          git-protocol proxy server developed under
#          the Fintech Open Source Foundation (FINOS)
#          that intercepts `git push` operations from
#          developer machines, applies a configurable
#          pipeline of inspection + approval + policy-
#          enforcement plugins (e.g. secret scanning,
#          file-type allow-lists, mandatory code-owner
#          review, dual-control approval workflows
#          required in regulated industries), then
#          forwards approved pushes to the actual
#          upstream git remote (GitHub Enterprise,
#          GitLab Self-Managed, Azure DevOps, Bitbucket
#          Data Center).
#          Distinguishing from server-side git hooks
#          (run AFTER push is accepted, can't block
#          fast-forward; bypassed by force-push;
#          require admin control of upstream), branch
#          protection rules (GitHub-specific; coarse
#          granularity; no audit trail of pre-push
#          context), pre-commit / pre-push client-side
#          hooks (can be bypassed with --no-verify;
#          no central enforcement), git-crypt
#          (encrypt-then-push pattern; doesn't catch
#          accidental secret exposure), and TruffleHog
#          / GitLeaks scanners (operate on existing
#          history; not push-time gating) by:
#            - PRE-PUSH GATING — sits in the network
#              path BETWEEN developer + git remote,
#              receiving the proposed push pack BEFORE
#              it lands upstream.  Can REJECT, MODIFY,
#              or QUEUE-FOR-REVIEW any push based on
#              policy
#            - ISOMORPHIC-GIT FOUNDATION — uses
#              isomorphic-git/isomorphic-git v1.36
#              (this is the headline CLI library that
#              CLOSES Axis 43 on the TS-Node side at
#              1/1/1; see taxonomy notes below) for ALL
#              git object-graph parsing + packfile
#              decoding + commit-tree traversal.  Pure-
#              JavaScript, runs in Node.js + browser
#              identically; the only major language
#              with a fully pure-language git
#              implementation that ALSO works in
#              browsers
#            - DUAL-CONTROL WORKFLOW — for regulated
#              industries (finance, healthcare,
#              defense) where SOX/Basel/HIPAA require
#              a second-party-approval before code
#              lands, git-proxy queues pushes for
#              human review via an Express + React
#              dashboard; reviewers see diffs (via
#              diff2html), commit metadata, file lists
#              before approving / rejecting
#            - PLUGIN ARCHITECTURE — `proxy.config.json`
#              declares a pipeline of plugins (secret
#              scanners, allow/deny lists, custom
#              regex checks, code-owner enforcement,
#              audit-log emitters); plugins are
#              authored as TypeScript modules
#              implementing a defined interface
#            - SECRET SCANNING BUILT-IN — bundled
#              plugins check for AWS access keys,
#              GitHub PATs, GitLab tokens, generic
#              high-entropy strings; configurable
#              entropy thresholds + per-plugin
#              allowlists
#            - DIFF2HTML PREVIEW — reviewers see push
#              contents rendered as side-by-side or
#              unified diffs via the diff2html library;
#              integrated into the React + Material UI
#              dashboard
#            - EXPRESS 5.x SERVER — HTTP + HTTPS
#              listeners forward to upstream git
#              remotes via express-http-proxy after
#              policy approval; rate-limited via
#              express-rate-limit; CSRF via session
#              middleware (express-session); session
#              storage via connect-mongo OR @seald-
#              io/nedb (embedded NoSQL)
#            - JWT + bcryptjs AUTH — JWT tokens for
#              dashboard + admin API auth; bcryptjs
#              for password hashing; works with
#              SAML/OIDC via additional adapters
#            - AWS-SDK CREDENTIAL HELPERS — bundled
#              @aws-sdk/credential-providers for
#              fetching IAM-role credentials when
#              git-proxy itself needs to authenticate
#              with upstream AWS-hosted git (e.g.
#              CodeCommit) on behalf of pushers
#            - YARGS CLI for SERVER STARTUP — the
#              `git-proxy` binary accepts `-c, --
#              config <path>` to point at a custom
#              proxy.config.json + `-v, --validate`
#              to check the config file for schema
#              compliance without starting the server
#            - GIT-PROXY-ALL COMPANION BINARY —
#              `git-proxy-all` is a concurrent runner
#              that launches both the server + the
#              client UI dev server simultaneously
#              (useful during development; uses
#              concurrently npm package)
#            - 211+ STARS ON finos/git-proxy — backed
#              by FINOS, the Fintech Open Source
#              Foundation (a Linux Foundation project
#              founded 2018 to promote open source in
#              financial services); contributors from
#              JP Morgan, Citi, Goldman Sachs, Morgan
#              Stanley, Bank of America, Deutsche
#              Bank, and other institutional members
#          Used by: financial-services institutions
#          requiring pre-merge policy enforcement
#          beyond what GitHub Enterprise / GitLab
#          Self-Managed provide natively, regulated
#          industries where SOX/Basel/HIPAA dual-
#          control requirements apply to source code
#          changes, security teams enforcing centralized
#          secret-scanning before code reaches the
#          authoritative remote, and any organization
#          where the cost of a leaked credential in
#          the upstream repo would be substantial.
#
# Author:  FINOS (Fintech Open Source Foundation;
#          https://www.finos.org), a Linux Foundation
#          project.  Repo maintained under
#          github.com/finos/git-proxy by a community
#          of contributors from financial-services
#          institutions including JP Morgan, Citi,
#          Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA, and
#          others.
# Source:  https://github.com/finos/git-proxy
#          https://github.com/finos/git-proxy/blob/main/index.ts
#          https://github.com/finos/git-proxy/blob/main/package.json
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `git-proxy --help`
#          shows yargs-generated help for the server
#          startup options.  Full architecture +
#          plugin docs in repo README.md + docs/.
# Library: isomorphic-git ^1.36.3 (isomorphic-git/
#          isomorphic-git — William Hilton's "A pure
#          JavaScript implementation of git for node
#          and browsers!").  This is the headline
#          dependency for this completion's axis-43
#          closing role; see taxonomy notes below.
#          Also yargs ^16 (Axis 1 argparse — used in
#          the CLI entry point), express ^5.2 (Axis
#          26 web framework — serves the proxy + UI),
#          express-http-proxy ^2.1 (forward layer),
#          express-rate-limit ^8.2, express-session
#          ^1.19, connect-mongo ^5.1 (session store
#          for MongoDB), @seald-io/nedb ^4.1 (embedded
#          NoSQL alternative session store), axios
#          ^1.13 (HTTP client), bcryptjs ^3 (Axis 17
#          password hashing), jsonwebtoken ^9 (JWT),
#          cors ^2.8, diff2html ^3.4 (rendered diff
#          previews), env-paths ^3 (XDG paths),
#          escape-string-regexp ^5, https-proxy-agent
#          ^7, @aws-sdk/credential-providers ^3.980
#          (AWS IAM for CodeCommit auth).  Dashboard
#          UI: React + @material-ui/core ^4.12 + @
#          primer/octicons-react + @fontsource/roboto.
